mpt to evade accountability for abuse and atrocity, using a range of well-known techniques including denial, delay, diversion, and delegation to pass blame for abuse and atrocities to the lowest plausible level. Mitchell argues that, despite the conventional wisdom that accountability is a ‘central feature’ of democracies, it is only a rare and courageous leader who acts differently, exposing the limits of accountability in democratic societies. As democracies remain embroiled in armed conflicts, and continue to try to come to grips with past atrocities, Democracy’s Blameless Leaders provides a timely analysis of why these events occur, why leaders behave as they do, and how a more accountable system might be developed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAtrocitiesvCase studies. 0aAtrocitiesxCase studies. 0aCivilians in warxCase studiesxCrimes against. 0aCivilians in warxCrimes againstvCase studies. 0aCriminal liability (International law)vCase studies. 0aCriminal liability (International law)xCase studies. 0aDemocracyxCase studiesxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aDemocracyxMoral and ethical aspectsvCase studies. 0aGovernment accountabilityvCase studies. 0aGovernment accountabilityxCase studies. 0aPolitical leadershipxCase studiesxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPolitical leadershipxMoral and ethical aspectsvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081476144140uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814761441.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814763377423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814763377/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-